\int_{\mathbb{R}^2}e^{-(x^2+y^2)}=\left(\int_\mathbb{R}e^{-x^2}\right)^2
e^{-(x^2+y^2)} = e^{-x^2}e^{-y^2}
\iint_{\mathbb R^2} e^{-(x^2+y^2)}\,dx\,dy = \int_{\mathbb R}e^{-x^2}\,dx\,\int_{\mathbb R}e^{-y^2}\,dy
\iint_{\mathbb R^2} e^{-(x^2+y^2)}\,dx\,dy = 2\pi \int_0^\infty  re^{-r^2}\,dr = -\pi   e^{-r^2}\bigg|_0^\infty   =\pi
